</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uevilnight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EvilNight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/20/02 3:12:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22881.topic&index=262>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: expansion smansion</span><hr size=1> Sequels for MMORPGs are a bad idea, at least in the traditional sense.<br>
<br>
Think about this from a business standpoint for a moment.<br>
<br>
First, you're going to be competing with yourself, there's simply no way to avoid it. People will not be paying to play both versions of the game at the same time, so you are not going to make any more money from your existing playerbase than what you already make.<br>
<br>
Also consider that setting up two versions of the game at the same time requires you to have two separate development teams (or one development and one support team if you stop all development on the original), and two separate server farms as well. You've greatly increased if not doubled your costs and the only new income you will be getting is from the new players attracted to the sequel game who were not previously playing the old game.<br>
<br>
No, conventional sequels won't work for the MMORPG market.<br>
<br>
Now, that's not saying a sequel game isn't possible. It's very possible, in fact it's almost a certainty. But what you will be doing is not creating a new game at the same time that the old one exists. You've got to do a migration from the old game to the new one. It would go something like this.<br>
<br>
VI does a lot of hardcore development work on the new game, EQ2. They import ALL old EQ content into the new game system (zones, MoBs, planes, names, text, items, whatever,  but NOT players at this point), recode it and change it to bring it up to date with the new game technology (and database technology, I'm sure EQ could use an update there as well), and put it into the sequel game. This is the point where they remove all the old problems and add all the new content. Problems like pathing, bad AI, broken quests, as well as basic game mechanics that are broken can all be fixed. You also do core updates to the game tech adding in or changing the skill system or whatever else you like... sky's the limit.<br>
<br>
Next, you write the new client, and get it working the way you want. It'd be a good idea to get a lot of player feedback on this.<br>
<br>
Note that you'll be breaking backwards compatibility at this point due to the large number of changes. EQ1 clients won't log into EQ2 servers, and vice versa.<br>
<br>
Bring up a brand new &quot;Everquest2&quot; server running the new game engine, new databases, new game content, whatever. You'd only need to run a few zones. Start the beta process and tweak things until they are ready for a real rollout. Start shipping the game.<br>
<br>
Now, the migration begins. Each day (or two, or three, or each week, depending on the difficulty of this), you bring down one of the existing servers, and destroy it, then replace it with the new EQ2 server. Good time for the much needed hardware upgrades.<br>
<br>
Repeat this process until all servers are migrated to EQ2 technology. At this point the old game is dead, maybe leave one server up for kicks.<br>
<br>
Now, as for characters, this is a more complicated process. I think that by and large, players will want to bring their characters over into EQ2. I certainly would be mad if they told me I had to start at the beginning again, and I'm sure I'm not alone. VI runs the risk of losing a lot of old players if they don't provide a way to keep your characters.<br>
<br>
They'll have to write an import utility. It'll read in your EQ1 character, and spit out the EQ2 version of it. There's no reason the new characters have to work by the old rules. You could revamp the skill system, heck even remove levels and leveling from the game, turn it into a skill system only. All that's necessary is a conversion utility, and that's trivial to write really, once the new system is designed.<br>
<br>
Run through that whole process every 3-5 years and you can keep one game going indefinitely, and keep building off the previous game's content. That's how I'd expect the game to become a sequel. <p>Raviel Darkfyre<BR>
